<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-089-650  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 089 650.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Educational Technology  Jan 1990 v30 n1 p41(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Transfer of learning and computer programming.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Martin, Bernadette; Hearne, J. Dixon.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Using computer software and programming are ways that students canapply and transfer problem solving skills such as means-endanalysis or systematic planning of actions to achieve certaingoals.andP;  The type of skill transferred depends upon what level ofcomputer skills the user knows.andP;  At the 'program user' level, orbeginning level, a student might learn when to use a computer tosolve a problem.andP;  At the 'software developer' level, a teachermight expect to see the most extensive evidence of cognitivetransfer.andP;  Both teachers and students may resist some transferopportunities because teaching models are often compartmentalized,with subjects such as math not being transferred or integratedinto different areas such as English or history.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     EducationComputer-Assisted InstructionProblem SolvingLOGOIntegrated ApproachComputer EducationTeaching.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>